  "prompt": "Why isn't the Moon spinning?",
  "response": "The Moon *is* spinning! It's just spinning in a way that makes it appear like it's not rotating to us on Earth. This is called **synchronous rotation** or **tidal locking**.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Rotation vs. Revolution:**\n    *   **Rotation** is the spinning of an object on its axis.\n    *   **Revolution** is the movement of an object around another object.\n\n*   **The Moon's Rotation:** The Moon rotates on its axis roughly once every 27.3 days. This is almost exactly the same amount of time it takes to orbit the Earth (revolve around the Earth).\n\n*   **Synchronous Rotation Explained:** Because the Moon's rotation and revolution periods are so closely matched, we always see the same face of the Moon from Earth. This makes it *seem* like the Moon isn't rotating, but it is. It's like if you walked around a table always facing the center, you'd be rotating even though you were constantly looking at the same spot.\n\n*   **Why Tidal Locking Occurred:**\n    *   **Tidal Forces:** The Earth's gravity exerts a tidal force on the Moon. This force is stronger on the side of the Moon closer to Earth than on the far side, creating a bulge.\n    *   **Early Moon:** When the Moon was younger and its crust was still molten, this bulge would have been much more pronounced.\n    *   **Friction and Alignment:** The Earth's gravity acted on this bulge, creating friction that slowed down the Moon's rotation over billions of years.  Eventually, the Moon's rotation slowed until its rotation period matched its orbital period, and the bulge aligned with the Earth.  At this point, the tidal forces no longer caused significant changes in the rotation rate.\n\n*   **Libration:** Although we mostly see the same face, we can actually see slightly more than 50% of the Moon's surface over time due to something called \"libration.\"  Libration has a few components:\n    *   **Libration in Longitude:**  The Moon's orbit isn't perfectly circular; it's slightly elliptical. This means the Moon's orbital speed varies slightly, but its rotation is relatively constant. So sometimes it \"leads\" its rotation a little, and sometimes it \"lags\" a little, allowing us to peek a bit around the eastern and western edges.\n    *   **Libration in Latitude:**  The Moon's axis of rotation is tilted slightly (about 6.7 degrees) relative to its orbital plane around Earth. This allows us to see a bit over the north and south poles at different times in its orbit.\n    *   **Diurnal Libration:** The Earth itself rotates, which changes our viewing angle of the Moon and allows for a small amount of additional viewing of the Moon's far side.\n\n**In short:** The Moon *does* spin. It's just that its spin is synchronized with its orbit around the Earth, making it appear as if it doesn't rotate from our perspective. This is due to tidal locking, a process caused by the Earth's gravitational influence on the Moon over billions of years.\n",
